1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:05,740
Python provides several built-in methods to make it easier to manage lists.

2

00:00:05,740  -->  00:00:10,485
Some of the most useful include append, insert, and index.

3

00:00:10,485  -->  00:00:14,320
Append is where we add an item to the end of the list.

4

00:00:14,320  -->  00:00:18,200
This is useful when we want to add items into our shopping cart.

5

00:00:18,200  -->  00:00:22,300
Insert adds an item at a specific index.

6

00:00:22,300  -->  00:00:26,380
This is useful if we want to add an item to our cart in a specific place,

7

00:00:26,380  -->  00:00:29,800
such as organizing fruits together or perishable items

8

00:00:29,800  -->  00:00:33,880
together so that they can go in the same bag for easier organization.

9

00:00:33,880  -->  00:00:39,130
Index, which finds the index of a specific item in the list.

10

00:00:39,130  -->  00:00:42,970
Think of this as using a powerful magnifying glass to identify

11

00:00:42,970  -->  00:00:45,670
the specific placement of an item in the list

12

00:00:45,670  -->  00:00:49,170
and tells us the index of that item in the collection.

13

00:00:49,170  -->  00:00:52,390
Just keep these things in mind for now.

14

00:00:52,390  -->  00:00:55,650
We're going to go through examples of these in some demos,

15

00:00:55,650  -->  00:00:59,820
so you can see these powerful methods of Python in action.

16

00:00:59,820  -->  00:01:02,925
Let's see some examples of the append, insert,

17

00:01:02,925  -->  00:01:06,420
and index functions in action using our fruit array.

18

00:01:06,420  -->  00:01:09,320
First, let's start off with the append function.

19

00:01:09,320  -->  00:01:13,600
Let's say we want to add another fruit to our list of fruits.

20

00:01:13,600  -->  00:01:18,040
How would we do that? Well, we can use the append function like this.

21

00:01:18,040  -->  00:01:21,245
We'll first create our list of fruits.

22

00:01:21,245  -->  00:01:24,100
We'll say fruits is equal to and in square brackets,

23

00:01:24,100  -->  00:01:27,955
apple, banana, and cherry as a list of strings.

24

00:01:27,955  -->  00:01:35,750
Then what we'll do is we will say fruits.append,

25

00:01:35,750  -->  00:01:38,790
and then inside of the append function,

26

00:01:38,790  -->  00:01:40,270
we'll add another fruit,

27

00:01:40,270  -->  00:01:42,110
which we'll say is grape.

28

00:01:42,110  -->  00:01:47,380
Then we'll print our updated list of fruits.

29

00:01:47,380  -->  00:01:52,110
Can you guess what the list of fruits will now look like?

30

00:01:52,830  -->  00:01:57,320
Now we see apple, banana, cherry, and grape.

31

00:01:57,320  -->  00:02:00,930
Now we've added grape to our last item in the list,

32

00:02:00,930  -->  00:02:03,710
and that's why it's at the end of it.

33

00:02:04,270  -->  00:02:08,670
If we want to add items to a specific location,

34

00:02:08,670  -->  00:02:10,490
how would we accomplish this?

35

00:02:10,490  -->  00:02:13,950
This is where our insert function comes into play.

36

00:02:13,950  -->  00:02:18,270
Now, we already have our fruits list already created.

37

00:02:18,270  -->  00:02:23,770
If we wanted to insert an item, we'll create a new cell,

38

00:02:23,770  -->  00:02:27,830
and we will say fruits in

39

00:02:27,830  -->  00:02:33,850
the position that we want that new item to go into at that index,

40

00:02:33,850  -->  00:02:35,550
and then we'll add in our new item,

41

00:02:35,550  -->  00:02:37,630
which we'll say is orange.

42

00:02:37,940  -->  00:02:43,875
Then we'll print the updated list of fruits.

43

00:02:43,875  -->  00:02:48,105
Can you guess what this will output?

44

00:02:48,105  -->  00:02:51,310
Let's run this and find out.

45

00:02:51,920  -->  00:02:57,470
Now, you'll notice we have grape at the end of our list that we

46

00:02:57,470  -->  00:03:02,310
added in the previous step and a new item orange as well.

47

00:03:02,310  -->  00:03:04,855
And this is at Index 1.

48

00:03:04,855  -->  00:03:07,325
This makes sense because it would be index zero,

49

00:03:07,325  -->  00:03:09,905
Index 1, and now we have 2, 3,

50

00:03:09,905  -->  00:03:12,850
4 because now we have one, two, three, four,

51

00:03:12,850  -->  00:03:17,150
five fruits in our fruits list now.

52

00:03:17,630  -->  00:03:22,490
Now, if we want to find the specific index of an item in our list,

53

00:03:22,490  -->  00:03:25,150
we can rely on our trusty index function.

54

00:03:25,150  -->  00:03:29,070
Let's see this working in an example here.

55

00:03:31,570  -->  00:03:35,730
If we wanted to check the index of banana,

56

00:03:35,730  -->  00:03:37,330
we would write something like this.

57

00:03:37,330  -->  00:03:44,300
We would say print fruits index banana.

58

00:03:44,330  -->  00:03:47,290
We pass in the item that we want to check,

59

00:03:47,290  -->  00:03:50,690
and we use the index function over our list,

60

00:03:50,690  -->  00:03:53,730
and that's the same list that we declared earlier.

61

00:03:53,730  -->  00:03:59,250
When we run this, we'll see two is the output.

62

00:03:59,250  -->  00:04:02,250
Here the index of this item is two,

63

00:04:02,250  -->  00:04:05,160
but originally, it was one.

64

00:04:05,160  -->  00:04:08,530
This is because we have a lot more items in the array than when we started,

65

00:04:08,530  -->  00:04:10,460
and we added orange.

66

00:04:10,460  -->  00:04:12,010
Originally, it was zero,

67

00:04:12,010  -->  00:04:13,585
one, Index 1,

68

00:04:13,585  -->  00:04:16,600
but now it's Index 2 as in index zero,

69

00:04:16,600  -->  00:04:19,190
Index 1, and Index 2.

70

00:04:19,880  -->  00:04:22,580
Same with grape.

71

00:04:22,580  -->  00:04:24,920
If we wanted to find the index of grape,

72

00:04:24,920  -->  00:04:31,060
we would write print index grape.

73

00:04:31,060  -->  00:04:34,240
Then we would execute that, and we'll see that that's Index 4,

74

00:04:34,240  -->  00:04:36,060
which makes sense because it's zero,

75

00:04:36,060  -->  00:04:39,360
one, two, three, four.

76

00:04:39,920  -->  00:04:42,720
Let's validate this is true.

77

00:04:42,720  -->  00:04:45,560
We'll write print fruits,

78

00:04:45,560  -->  00:04:47,825
and then we'll press Enter.

79

00:04:47,825  -->  00:04:52,920
Can you guess what the output will be for all of the fruits?

80

00:04:53,870  -->  00:04:56,145
We'll see five items.

81

00:04:56,145  -->  00:04:57,840
If you guess this, you're right.

82

00:04:57,840  -->  00:04:59,950
We'll see apple, orange,

83

00:04:59,950  -->  00:05:02,150
banana, cherry, and grape.

84

00:05:02,150  -->  00:05:05,050
We can verify that this is Index zero,

85

00:05:05,050  -->  00:05:10,210
one, two, three, and four. Great job.
